\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first recall a few definitions from point-set topology.
 A topological space is 
\series bold
second countable
\series default
 if it has a countable basis.
 A 
\series bold
neighborhood
\series default
 of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is any open set containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
Hausdorff
\series default
 if for every pair of points 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M$
\end_inset

, there exists a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 An 
\series bold
open cover
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 whose union 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i\in I}U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The Hausdorff condition and second countability are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hereditary properties
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; they are inherited by subspaces: a subspace of a Hausdorff space is Hausdorff.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 be a subspace of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is second countable, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 is second countable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(1):$
\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff, choose a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $U'=U\cap M'$
\end_inset

 is a neighboorhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the subspace topology and 
\begin_inset Formula $V'=V\cap M'$
\end_inset

 is a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the subspace topology and 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\cap V'=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(2):$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\{B_{i}\}_{i\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 is a countable basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{B_{i}'\}_{i\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 is a countable basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}'=B_{i}\cap M'$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
locally Euclidean of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 such that there is a homeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 onto an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We call the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
chart
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
coordinate neighborhood
\series default
 or a 
\series bold
coordinate open set
\series default
, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
coordinate map
\series default
 or a 
\series bold
coordinate system on 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 We say that a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
centered
\series default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 be a chart on the topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\phi|_{V})$
\end_inset

 is a chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This follows from the fact that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\to\phi(U)$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi|_{V}:V\to\phi(V)$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
topological manifold
\series default
 is a Hausdorff, second countable, locally Euclidean space.
 It is said to be of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 if it is locally Euclidean of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is covered by a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}^{n},1_{\mathbb{R}^{n}})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the identity map.
 It is the prime example of a topological manifold.
 Every open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is also a topological manifold, with chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,1_{U})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (A cusp).
 The graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{2/3}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a topological manifold.
 By virtue of being a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, it is Hausdorff and second countable.
 It is locally Euclidean because it is homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 via the projection 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,x^{2/3})\mapsto x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines=none, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmax=5, xmin=-5, ymax=5, ymin=-5, ]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red, samples=60] ({x^3},{4*x^2});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (A cross).
 The cross can be described as 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(r,0)\mid r\in\mathbb{R}\}\cup\{(0,r)\mid r\in\mathbb{R}\}$
\end_inset

.
 We show that the cross in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 with the subspace topology is not locally Euclidean at the intersection
 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(0,0)$
\end_inset

, and so cannot be a manifold.
 Suppose the cross is locally Euclidean of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 has a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 homeomorphic to an open ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B:=B_{\varepsilon}(0)\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 mapping to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 The homeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $U\to B$
\end_inset

 restricts to a homemorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $U\setminus\{p\}\to B\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $B\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is either connected if 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

 or has two connected components of 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U\setminus\{p\}$
\end_inset

 has four connected components, there can be no homeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $U\setminus\{p\}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B\setminus\{p\}$
\end_inset

.
 This contradiction proves that the cross is not locally Euclidean at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

