\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Compatible Charts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi:V\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 of a topological manifold are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset


\series bold
 compatible
\series default
 if the two maps 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\circ\psi^{-1}:\psi(U\cap V)\to\phi(U\cap V)\qquad\psi\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U\cap V)\to\psi(U\cap V)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 These two maps are called the 
\series bold
transition functions
\series default
 between the charts.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 is empty, then the two charts are automatically 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 compatible.
 To simplify this notation, we will sometimes write 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap U_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ijk}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap U_{j}\cap U_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 We will also sometimes write 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}\circ\phi_{j}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since we are interested only in 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible charts, we often omit mention of 
\begin_inset Formula $"C^{\infty}"$
\end_inset

 and speak simply of compatible charts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 compatibility is clearly reflexive and symmetric, but not necessarily transitiv
e.
 Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 compatible with 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 compatible with 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{3},\phi_{3})$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the three coordinate functions are simultaneously defined only
 on the triple intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{123}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the composite
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{3}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}=(\phi_{3}\circ\phi_{2})^{-1}\circ(\phi_{2}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1})
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, but only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{123})$
\end_inset

, not necessarily on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{13})$
\end_inset

.
 A priori we know nothing about 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{3}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{13}\setminus U_{123})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Atlas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
atlas
\series default
 or simply an 
\series bold
atlas 
\series default
on a locally Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}=\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of pairwise 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 compatible charts such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 covers 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlas on a circle).
 The unit circle 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 in the complex plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 may be described as the set of points 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e^{2\pi it}\in\mathbb{C}\mid0\leq t\leq1\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the two open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=\{e^{2\pi it}\in\mathbb{C}\mid-\frac{1}{2}<t<\frac{1}{2}\}\qquad U_{2}=\{e^{2\pi it}\in\mathbb{C}\mid0<t<1\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=red] (2,0) circle (1cm);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=red] (-2,0) circle (1cm);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=white, inner sep=0.5pt, label=below left:$$] (x) at (-3,0)
 {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=white, inner sep=0.5pt, label=below left:$$] (x) at (3,0)
 {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[label=below:$ U_1 $] (x) at (-2,2) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[label=below:$ U_2 $] (x) at (2,2) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and define 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}:U_{i}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{1}(e^{2\pi it})=t\qquad\phi_{2}(e^{2\pi it})=t
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

 are branches of the complex log funciton 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/i)\log z$
\end_inset

 and are homeomorphisms onto their respective images.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

 are charts on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{12}$
\end_inset

 consists of two connected components, the lower half 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and the upper half 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\{e^{2\pi it}\mid-\frac{1}{2}<t<0\}\qquad B=\{e^{2\pi it}\mid0<t<\frac{1}{2}\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{1}(U_{12})=\phi_{1}(A\cup B)=\phi_{1}(A)\cup\phi_{1}(B)=\left(-\frac{1}{2},0\right)\cup\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{2}(U_{12})=\phi_{2}(A\cup B)=\phi_{2}(A)\cup\phi_{2}(B)=\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right)\cup\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transisition function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}:\phi_{1}(U_{12})\to\phi_{2}(U_{12})$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\phi_{2}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1})(t)=\begin{cases}
t+1 & \mbox{for }t\in\left(-\frac{1}{2},0\right)\\
t & \mbox{for }t\in\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1})(t)=\begin{cases}
t-1 & \mbox{for }t\in\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right)\\
t & \mbox{for }t\in\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible charts and form a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Compatibility With Atlas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}=\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas a locally Euclidean space.
 We say that a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
compatible with
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 if it is compatible with all the charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},\phi_{i})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{compatible}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}=\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas on a locally Euclidean space.
 If two charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(W,\sigma)$
\end_inset

 are both compatible with the atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

, then they are compatible with each other.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(V\cap W)$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\sigma^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(V\cap W)$
\end_inset

 will follow by a similar argument.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma\circ\psi^{-1}|_{\psi(V\cap W\cap U_{i})}=(\sigma\circ\phi_{i}^{-1})\circ(\phi_{i}\circ\psi^{-1})|_{\psi(V\cap W\cap U_{i})}
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(V\cap W\cap U_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigcup_{i\in I}\psi(V\cap W\cap U_{i})=\psi(V\cap W).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Standardized and Maximal Atlas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
standardized 
\series default
if it has no repetitions in the sense that whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 we have that either 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\neq U_{j}$
\end_inset

 or, when 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=U_{j}$
\end_inset

, the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i},\phi_{j}:U_{i}\to\mathbb{R}^{n_{i}}$
\end_inset

 do not coincide.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}'$
\end_inset

 are standarized 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 atlases on a locally Euclidean space, then it makes sense to ask if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}\subseteq\mathcal{A}'$
\end_inset

.
 This means that each 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi,U)\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is equal to some 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi',U')\in\mathcal{A}'$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equality
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means 
\begin_inset Formula $U=U'$
\end_inset

 and the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi,\phi':U\rightrightarrows\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 coincide.
 We say that a standardized atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}'$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
dominates 
\series default
a standardized atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}\subseteq\mathcal{A}'$
\end_inset

 in the senese just defined.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Unless otherwise specified, we shall always assume that a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 atlas is standardized.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

An atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

 on a locally Euclidean space is said to be 
\series bold
maximal
\series default
 if it is not strictly contained in a larger atlas.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 Manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 manifold is a topological manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 together with a maximal atlas.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\infty$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
smooth 
\series default
and the maximal atlas is called a 
\series bold
differentiable structure
\series default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 A manifold is said to have dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 if all of its connected components have dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold is also called a 
\series bold
curve
\series default
.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold is a 
\series bold
surface
\series default
, and an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-manifold.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In practice, to check that a topological manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 manifold, it is not necessary to exhibit a maximal atlas.
 The existence of any atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 will do, because of the following proposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}=\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 on a locally Euclidean space is contained in a unique maximal atlas.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Adjoin to the atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 all charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(V_{i},\psi_{i})$
\end_inset

 that are compatible with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{compatible})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(V_{i},\psi_{i})$
\end_inset

 are compatible with one another.
 So the enlarged collection of charts is an atlas.
 Any chart compatible with the new atlas must be compatible with the original
 atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 and so by construction belongs to the new atlas.
 This proves existence.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}'$
\end_inset

 is another maximal atlas containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

, then all the charts in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}'$
\end_inset

 are compatible with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 and so by construction must belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This proves 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}'\subset\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Since both are maximal, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}'=\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This proves uniqueness.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In summary, to show that a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 manifold, it suffices to check that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff and second countable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 atlas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A topological manifold can be endowed with different (non-compatible) different
iable structures.
 For instance, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We can give the space the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 manifold using the single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R},\varphi_{1})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to x$
\end_inset

.
 We can also give the space the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 manifold using the single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R},\varphi_{2})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto x^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 These two charts are not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatible since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}\circ\varphi_{2}^{-1}:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto x^{\frac{1}{3}}$
\end_inset

, and this is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dx}\left(x^{\frac{1}{3}}\right)=\frac{1}{3}x^{-\frac{2}{3}}$
\end_inset

 is not continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
An Atlas For a Product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propproductofmanifolds}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}=\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\mid i\in I\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{V}=\{(V_{j},\psi_{j})\mid j\in J\}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlases for the manifolds 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, respectively, then the collection 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{U}\times\mathfrak{V}=\{(U_{i}\times V_{j},\phi_{i}\times\psi_{j}:U_{i}\times V_{j}\to\mathbb{R}^{m}\times\mathbb{R}^{n})\mid(i,j)\in I\times J\}
\]

\end_inset

of charts is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $m+n$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Clearly the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ U_{i}\times V_{j}\mid(i,j)\in I\times J\right\} $
\end_inset

 covers 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

, so we just need to show that any two charts in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}\times\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

 are pairwise compatible.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1}\times V_{1},\phi_{1}\times\psi_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2}\times V_{2},\phi_{2}\times\psi_{2})$
\end_inset

 be two charts in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}\times\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\phi_{1}\times\psi_{1}\right)\circ\left(\phi_{2}\times\psi_{2}\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\phi_{1}\times\psi_{1}\right)\circ\left(\phi_{2}\times\psi_{2}\right)^{-1}=\left(\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1}\right)\times\left(\psi_{2}\times\psi_{2}^{-1}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}\times\psi_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on their respective domains.
 The same proof shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\phi_{2}\times\psi_{2}\right)\circ\left(\phi_{1}\times\psi_{1}\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}\times\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of pairwise 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatible charts that cover 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propproductofmanifolds})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that the infinite cylinder 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and the torus 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

 are manifolds.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of Smooth Manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Euclidean Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Euclidean space).
 The Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth manifold with a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}^{n},\text{id})$
\end_inset

.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 to denote coordinates functions and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}$
\end_inset

 to denote real numbers.
 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(p)=a_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(p)=a_{2}$
\end_inset

, and etc...
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The real half line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{>0}:\{a\in\mathbb{R}\mid a>0\}$
\end_inset

 is also a smooth manifold, with a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}_{>0},\text{id})$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{>0}$
\end_inset

 is homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 A homeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{>0}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{log}:\mathbb{R}_{>0}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now consider the half-open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,2\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 Open sets of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 where and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq a<b<2\pi$
\end_inset

 form a basis for this topological space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Right-Half Infinite Strip and the Right-Half Plane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{R}_{>0}\times$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{-\pi}{2},\frac{\pi}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We illustrate this space below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw [dashed, fill=gray!20] (-10,-2) rectangle (10,2);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=white] (10,2) -- (10,-2);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=red] (-10,0.5) -- (10,0.5);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
