\begin_layout Standard
We can give both 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 the structure of a smooth manifold by simply using the identity charts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:M\to N$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(r,\theta)=(\varphi_{1}(r,\theta),\varphi_{2}(r,\theta))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{1}(r,\theta) & =r\sin\theta\\
\varphi_{2}(r,\theta) & =r\cos\theta
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,\theta)\in M$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{(r,\theta)}(\varphi)=\begin{pmatrix}\sin\theta & r\cos\theta\\
\cos\theta & -r\sin\theta
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:M\to N$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:N\to M$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(a,b)=(\psi_{1}(a,b),\psi_{2}(a,b))$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{1}(a,b) & =\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}}\\
\psi_{2}(a,b) & =\arctan\left(\frac{a}{b}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in N$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{(a,b)}(\psi)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}}}\begin{pmatrix}a & b\\
-b & a
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Manifolds of Dimension Zero
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Manifolds of dimension zero).
 In a manifold of dimension zero, every singleton subset is homeomorphic
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{0}$
\end_inset

 and so is open.
 Thus, a zero-dimensional manifold is a discrete set.
 By second countability, this discrete set must be countable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Graph of a Smooth Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Graph of a smooth function).
 For a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, the 
\series bold
graph
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the subset
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma(f)=\{(p,f(p))\in A\times\mathbb{R}^{n}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, then the two maps 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi:\Gamma(f)\to U\qquad(p,f(p))\mapsto p
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1,f):U\to\Gamma(f)\qquad p\mapsto(p,f(p))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
are continuous and inverse to each other, and so are homeomorphisms.
 The graph 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(f)$
\end_inset

 of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 has an atlas with a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Gamma(f),\phi)$
\end_inset

, and is therefore a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold.
 This shows that many familiar surfaces of calculus, for example an elliptic
 paraboloid or a hyperbolic paraboloid, are manifolds.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Circle 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{examplecirclestereographic}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Circle) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 be the unit circle centered at the origin in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{1}=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x^{2}+y^{2}=1\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall describe an atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 using stereographic projection.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}=S^{1}\backslash\{(-1,0)\}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the line 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 which passes through the points 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,t)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The equation of this line is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=t(X+1).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 passes through 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 and is not tangent to 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,0)$
\end_inset

, it must pass through a unique point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This is illustrated in the image below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines = none, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmin=-3,xmax=3,ymin=-3,ymax=3,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xtick=
\backslash
empty ,ytick=
\backslash
empty ,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

axis equal,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,samples=80] ({cos(deg(x))},{sin(deg(x))}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,samples=80] ({0},{x}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,samples=80] ({x},{2*x + 2}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.3pt, label=left:$ (-1
\backslash
text{,}0) $] (a) at (axis cs:-1,0) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.3pt, label=left:$(x
\backslash
text{,}y)$] (c) at (axis cs:-0.6,0.8) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.3pt, label=left:$(0
\backslash
text{,}t)$] (b) at (axis cs:0,2) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 lies on the line 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and the unit circle, we get the relations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{2}+y^{2}-1 & =0,\\
y-t(x+1) & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the second relation, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y=t(x+1)$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging in 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x+1)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the first relation, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t^{2}=\frac{(1-x)^{2}}{(1+x)^{2}}=\frac{1-x}{1+x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, to get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =\frac{1-t^{2}}{1+t^{2}},\\
y & =\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}:U_{1}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x,y)\mapsto\frac{y}{1+x}.
\]

\end_inset

This map is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in its domain 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq-1$
\end_inset

, and the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}^{-1}:\mathbb{R}\to U_{1}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t\mapsto\left(\frac{1-t^{2}}{1+t^{2}},\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}=S^{1}\backslash\{(1,0)\}$
\end_inset

.
 Following the same line of reasoning as the paragraph above, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}:U_{2}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x,y)\mapsto\frac{y}{1-x}.
\]

\end_inset

Again, this map is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in its domain 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq1$
\end_inset

, and the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}^{-1}:\mathbb{R}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t\mapsto\left(\frac{t^{2}-1}{1+t^{2}},\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us calculate the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{12}:=\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{12}(t) & =(\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1})(t)\\
 & =\phi_{1}\left(\frac{t^{2}-1}{1+t^{2}},\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{t}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We think of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as a local coordinate of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 as global coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Projective Line
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be the projective line over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Define in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 the two charts given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{0}=D(X_{0})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{0}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{0}(x_{0}:x_{1})=\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}\in\mathbb{R},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=D(X_{1})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{1}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(x_{0}:x_{1})=\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}\in\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These maps are clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in their domains.
 The inverse maps are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{0}^{-1}(t)=(1:t)\in U_{0}\qquad\phi_{1}^{-1}(t)=(t:1)\in U_{1}.
\]

\end_inset

Now let's calculate the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}:=\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}(t) & =\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}\left(t\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(t:1\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{t}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that this is the same transition map we calculated in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{examplecirclestereographic})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{examplesphere}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Sphere) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 be the unit sphere 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{2}=\{(a,b,c)\in\mathbb{R}^{3}\mid a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}=1\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Define in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 the six charts corresponding to the six hemispheres - the front, rear,
 right , left, upper, and lower hemispheres
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid a>0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(a,b,c)=(b,c)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{2}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid a<0\}\qquad\phi_{2}(a,b,c)=(b,c)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{3}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid b>0\}\qquad\phi_{3}(a,b,c)=(a,c)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{4}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid b<0\}\qquad\phi_{4}(a,b,c)=(a,c)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{5}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid c>0\}\qquad\phi_{5}(a,b,c)=(a,b)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{6}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid c<0\}\qquad\phi_{6}(a,b,c)=(a,b)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{14}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid b<0<a\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{4}(U_{14})=\{(a,c)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid a^{2}+c^{2}<1\text{ and }a>0\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us do some computations.
 First, let's compute the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{14}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{14}(a,c) & =\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{4}^{-1}(a,c)\\
 & =\phi_{1}\left(a,\sqrt{1-c^{2}-a^{2}},c\right)\\
 & =\left(\sqrt{1-c^{2}-a^{2}},c\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It is easy to see that this is indeed a smooth map in its domain (since
 
\begin_inset Formula $1-c^{2}-a^{2}\neq0$
\end_inset

).
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{14}$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,c)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{(a,c)}(\phi_{14})=\begin{pmatrix}\frac{a}{\sqrt{1-c^{2}-a^{2}}} & \frac{c}{\sqrt{1-c^{2}-a^{2}}}\\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's compute the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{45}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{45}(a,b) & =\phi_{4}\circ\phi_{5}^{-1}(a,b)\\
 & =\phi_{4}\left(a,b,\sqrt{1-a^{2}-b^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\left(a,\sqrt{1-a^{2}-b^{2}}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{nsphere}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Using stereographic projections (from the north pole and the south pole),
 we can define two charts on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 and show that 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth manifold.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{N}=(0,\dots,0,1)\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 be the north pole and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{S}=(0,\dots,0,-1)\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 be the south pole.
 Define the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{N}:S^{n}\backslash\{p_{N}\}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{S}:S^{n}\backslash\{p_{S}\}$
\end_inset

, called 
\series bold
stereographic projection 
\series default
from the north pole (resp.
 south pole), by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{N}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n+1})=\frac{1}{1-x_{n+1}}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\quad\text{and}\quad\phi_{S}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n+1})=\frac{1}{1+x_{n+1}}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

The inverse stereographic projections are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{N}^{-1}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})=\frac{1}{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}\left(2x_{1},\dots,2x_{n},-1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{S}^{-1}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})=\frac{1}{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}\left(2x_{1},\dots,2x_{n},1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Thus, if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}=S^{n}\backslash\{p_{N}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{S}=S^{n}\backslash\{p_{S}\}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{S}$
\end_inset

 are two open subsets convering 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

, both homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, it is easily checked that on the overlap, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}\cap U_{S}$
\end_inset

, the transition maps 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{S}\circ\phi_{N}^{-1}=\phi_{N}\circ\phi_{S}^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\mapsto\frac{1}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}),
\]

\end_inset

that is, the inversion of center 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O}=(0,\dots,0)$
\end_inset

 and power 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, this map is smooth on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\backslash\{O\}$
\end_inset

, so we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{N},\phi_{N})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{S},\phi_{S})$
\end_inset

 form a smooth atlas for 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Real Projective Plane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{exampleprojectiveplane}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Projective Plane) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be the projective plane over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Define in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 the three charts given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{0}=D(X_{0})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid x_{0}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{0}(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})=\left(\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{0}}\right)=:(a,b)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=D(X_{1})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid x_{1}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})=\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)=:(c,d)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{2}=D(X_{2})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid x_{2}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{2}(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})=\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{2}},\frac{x_{1}}{x_{2}}\right)=:(e,f)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism is because given that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\neq0$
\end_inset

, we use the equivalence relation to write the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}:1:\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}$
\end_inset

 are two real rumbers which uniquely determine the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 We think of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 as the local coordinates in the 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{0},\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 chart.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{01}$
\end_inset

 be the intersection of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{01}:=\{(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid x_{0}\neq0\text{ and }x_{1}\neq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}(U_{01})=\left\{ \left(\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{0}}\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x_{0}\neq0\text{ and }x_{1}\neq0\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})=\left\{ \left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x_{0}\neq0\text{ and }x_{1}\neq0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We can also write this in terms of local coordinates as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}(U_{01})=\{(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid a\neq0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})=\{(c,d)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid c\neq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Now let's calculate the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}:=\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}:\phi_{1}(U_{01})\to\phi_{0}(U_{01})$
\end_inset

 using the local coordinates.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{01}\left(c,d\right) & =\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}\left(c,d\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}:1:\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(1:\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}:\frac{x_{2}}{x_{0}}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{0}}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{c},\frac{d}{c}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It's easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{2}$
\end_inset

 for the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{1}(c,d)=\frac{1}{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{2}(c,d)=\frac{d}{c}$
\end_inset

), the partial derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{c}^{m}\partial_{d}^{n}\phi_{01}^{i}$
\end_inset

 exist and are continuous everywhere in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

.
 This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are rational functions (i.e.
 ratio of two polynomials) and are they are defined everywhere since 
\begin_inset Formula $c\neq0$
\end_inset

 in
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Similarly, one can easily show that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\phi_{10}\left(a,b\right) & =\left(\frac{1}{a},\frac{b}{a}\right)\\
\phi_{20}\left(a,b\right) & =\left(\frac{1}{b},\frac{a}{b}\right)\\
\phi_{02}\left(e,f\right) & =\left(\frac{f}{e},\frac{1}{e}\right)\\
\phi_{12}\left(e,f\right) & =\left(\frac{e}{f},\frac{1}{f}\right)\\
\phi_{21}(c,d) & =\left(\frac{c}{d},\frac{1}{d}\right)
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

It is instructive to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}\circ\phi_{ji}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}\circ\phi_{jk}=\phi_{ik}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Riemann Sphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Riemann sphere) In this example we describe a 
\series bold
complex manifold
\series default
.
 A complex manifold is the complex analogue of a manifold, however in the
 complex manifold case, we require the transition maps to be holomorphic,
 and not just 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

 be the projective line over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 (also known as the Riemann sphere).
 Define in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

 the two charts given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{0}=D(X_{0})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{0}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{0}(x_{0}:x_{1})=\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=D(X_{1})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{1}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(x_{0}:x_{1})=\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This time, let 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 The open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{01}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{0}\neq0\text{ and }x_{1}\neq0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})=\mathbb{C}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Now
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}(z) & =\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}:1\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(1:\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}\\
 & =\frac{1}{z}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can show that the map 
\begin_inset Formula $z\mapsto\frac{1}{z}$
\end_inset

 is holomorphic in the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Mobius Strip
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to give this set the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-manifold.
 First we consider the set of all nonvertical lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 A nonvertial is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a,b}^{v}=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid y=ax+b\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each such line is uniquely determined by a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So we have bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}:U_{v}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a,b}^{v}\mapsto(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 We give 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

 a topology using the bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

 into a homeomorphism.
 Next we consider the set of all nonhorizontal lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

.
 A nonhorizontal is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{c,d}^{h}=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x=cy+d\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each such line is uniquely determined by a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(c,d)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So we have bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}:U_{h}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{c,d}^{h}\mapsto(c,d)$
\end_inset

.
 We give 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

 a topology using the bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}$
\end_inset

 into a homeomorphism.
 Now we have 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}\cup U_{h}=\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

.
 To get a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

, we glue the topologies from 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{h}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Let's calculate the transition maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{vh}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{hv}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{vh}(c,d) & =\varphi_{v}\circ\varphi_{h}^{-1}(c,d)\\
 & =\varphi_{v}\left(\ell_{c,d}^{h}\right)\\
 & =\varphi_{v}\left(\ell_{\frac{1}{c},-\frac{d}{c}}^{v}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{c},-\frac{d}{c}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{hv}(a,b) & =\varphi_{h}\circ\varphi_{v}^{-1}(a,b)\\
 & =\varphi_{h}\left(\ell_{a,b}^{v}\right)\\
 & =\varphi_{h}\left(\ell_{\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}}^{h}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These maps are clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, they look very similar to the transition maps for the projective
 plane, except they are twisted by a negative sign.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We can also describe 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{2}\backslash\{[0:0:1]\}$
\end_inset

: Any line in the euclidean plane is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+by+c=0$
\end_inset

, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 First note that these coefficients uniquely determine the line and they
 are homogeneous.
 Hence there is a well defined map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathcal{L}\to\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by mapping the line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(ax+by+c)$
\end_inset

 to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $[a:b:c]$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is injective, but not surjective.
 However if we remove the point 
\begin_inset Formula $[0:0:1]$
\end_inset

, then the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathcal{L}\to\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{2}\backslash\{[0:0:1]\}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Grassmannians
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The 
\series bold
Grassmannian 
\begin_inset Formula $G(k,n)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-planes through the origin in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-plane is a linear subspace of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and has a basis consisting of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 linearly independent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},\dots,v_{k}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 It is therefore completely specified by an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A=[a_{1}\cdots a_{k}]$
\end_inset

 of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, where the 
\series bold
rank 
\series default
of a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{rk}A$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the number of linearly independent columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 This matrix is called a 
\series bold
matrix representative 
\series default
of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-plane.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Two bases 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},\dots,b_{k}$
\end_inset

 determine the same 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-plane if there is a change-of-basis matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $g=[g_{ij}]\in\text{GL}(k,\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{j}=\sum_{i=1}^{k}a_{i}g_{ij}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 In matrix notation, this says 
\begin_inset Formula $B=Ag$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F(k,n)$
\end_inset

 be the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times k$
\end_inset

 matrices of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, topologized as a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n\times k}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 the equivalence relation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\sim B\text{ if and only if there is a matrix }g\in\text{GL}(k,\mathbb{R})\text{ such that }B=Ag.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a bijection between 
\begin_inset Formula $G(k,n)$
\end_inset

 and the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $F(k,n)/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 We give the Grassmannian 
\begin_inset Formula $G(k,n)$
\end_inset

 the quotient topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $F(k,n)/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A 
\series bold
real Grassmann manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $G(n,k)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is defined as the space of all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-dimensional subspaces of the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The topology in 
\begin_inset Formula $G(n,k)$
\end_inset

 may be described as induced by the embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $G(n,k)\to\text{End}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 which assigns to a 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in G(n,k)$
\end_inset

, the orthogonal projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\to P$
\end_inset

 combined with the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $P\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In 
\begin_inset Formula $G(4,2)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & a_{12} & a_{13} & a_{14}\\
a_{21} & a_{22} & a_{23} & a_{24}
\end{pmatrix}\sim\begin{pmatrix}c_{11} & c_{12}\\
c_{21} & c_{22}
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & a_{12} & a_{13} & a_{14}\\
a_{21} & a_{22} & a_{23} & a_{24}
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}c_{11}a_{11}+c_{12}a_{21} & c_{11}a_{12}+c_{12}a_{22} & c_{11}a_{13}+c_{12}a_{23} & c_{11}a_{14}+c_{12}a_{24}\\
c_{21}a_{11}+c_{22}a_{21} & c_{11}a_{12}+c_{12}a_{22} & c_{11}a_{13}+c_{12}a_{23} & c_{11}a_{14}+c_{12}a_{24}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{11}c_{22}-c_{21}c_{12}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Smooth Maps on a Manifold
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we've defined smooth manifolds, it is time to consider maps between
 them.
 Using coordinate charts, one can transfer the notion of smooth maps from
 Euclidean spaces to manifolds.
 By the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatibility of charts in an atlas, the smoothness of a map turns out
 to be independent of the choice of charts and is therefore well defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Smooth Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a smooth manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 or 
\series bold
smooth at a point 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if there is a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},\phi_{i})$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, a function defined on the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}(p)$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 For each open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{M}^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

 to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra of smooth functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{C}_{M}^{\infty}(U): & =\{f:U\to\mathbb{R}\mid f\text{ is }C^{\infty}\text{ on }U\}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a smooth manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(\phi_{i},U_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{M}^{\infty}(U)\simeq\left\{ (g_{i})_{i}\in\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{C}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}^{\infty}(U_{i})\mid\phi_{ji}^{*}(g_{i}|_{U_{ij}})=g_{j}|_{U_{ij}}\text{ for all }i,j\in I\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{C}_{M}^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}\in\mathcal{C}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}^{\infty}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we get a map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi:f\mapsto(f\circ\phi_{i}^{-1})_{i}\in\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{C}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}^{\infty}(U_{i}),
\]

\end_inset

and it is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $(f\circ\phi_{i}^{-1})_{i}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the compatibility condition, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{ji}^{*}(f\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}|_{U_{ij}})=f\circ\phi_{j}^{-1}|_{U_{ij}}.
\]

\end_inset

 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(g_{i})_{i}\in\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{C}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}^{\infty}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}^{*}(g_{i}|_{U_{ij}})=g_{j}|_{U_{ij}}\text{ for all }i,j\in I$
\end_inset

, then writing 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}:=g_{i}\circ\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=f_{j}|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

.
 These glue to a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The definition of the smoothness of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point is independent of the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

, for if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is any other chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\circ\psi^{-1}\mid_{\psi(U\cap V)}=(f\circ\phi^{-1})\circ(\phi\circ\psi^{-1})
\]

\end_inset

is a composition of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions and hence must be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the definition above, 
\begin_inset Formula $f:M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is not assumed to be continuous.
 However, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, being a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

 in an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 As a composite of continuous functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U}=(f\circ\phi^{-1})\circ\phi$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Since we are only interested in functions that are smooth on an open set,
 there is no loss of generality in assuming at the onset that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a smooth manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 be a chart of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6.3}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 a real-valued function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The following are equivalent: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has an atlas such that for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 in the atlas, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\supset\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\psi^{-1}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\supset\psi(V)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will prove the proposition as a cyclic chain of implications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

1): This follows directly from the definition of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function, since by (2) every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

 has a coordinate neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

3): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in V$
\end_inset

.
 By the remark above, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 was an arbitrary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(V)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
