\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

2): Obvious.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The smoothness conditions of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop6.3})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 will be a recurrent motif: to prove the smoothness of an object, it is
 sufficient that a smoothness criterion hold on the charts of some atlas.
 Once the object is shown to be smooth, it then follows that the same smoothness
 criterion holds on 
\emph on
every 
\emph default
chart.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 be a map and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 a function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
pullback 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{*}h$
\end_inset

, is the composite function 
\begin_inset Formula $h\circ F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In this terminology, a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 if and only if its pullback 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi^{-1})^{*}f$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on the subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U)$
\end_inset

 of Euclidean space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 be rotation counterclockwise by an angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 denote the standard coordinate functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi^{*}x & =(\cos\theta)x-(\sin\theta)y\\
\phi^{*}y & =(\sin\theta)x+(\cos\theta)y.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},e_{2}$
\end_inset

 denote the standard coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

; so 
\begin_inset Formula $x(e_{1})=$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\phi^{*}x)(a,b) & =x\left(\phi(a,b)\right)\\
 & =x\left(\cos\theta a-\sin\theta b,\sin\theta a+\cos\theta b\right)\\
 & =\cos\theta a-\sin\theta b\\
 & =((\cos\theta)x-(\sin\theta)y)(a,b).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Smooth Maps Between Manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We emphasize again that unless otherwise specified, by a manifold we always
 mean a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold.
 We use the terms 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 interchangeably.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be manifolds of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 A continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
at a point 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 if there are charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 such that the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

, a map from the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(F^{-1}(V)\cap U)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 The continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the definition, we needed 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 to be open so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(F^{-1}(V)\cap U)$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps between manifolds are by definition continuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In case 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, we can take 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}^{m},1_{\mathbb{R}^{m}})$
\end_inset

 as a chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 According to the definition above, 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

 if and only if there is a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, we recover the definition of a function being 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at a point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We show now that the definition of the smoothness of a map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 at a point is independent of the choice of charts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6.7}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is any chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is any chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

, there are charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{\alpha},\phi_{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V_{\beta},\psi_{\beta})$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\beta}\circ F\circ\phi_{\alpha}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}(p)$
\end_inset

.
 By the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatibility of charts in a differentiable structure, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\psi_{\beta}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on open subsets of Euclidean spaces.
 Hence, the composite
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}|_{\phi\left(F^{-1}(V\cap V_{\beta})\cap U\cap U_{\alpha}\right)}=(\psi\circ\psi_{\beta}^{-1})\circ(\psi_{\beta}\circ F\circ\phi_{\alpha}^{-1})\circ(\phi_{\alpha}\circ\phi^{-1}),
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../Notes_190117_135420_7a4_1.jpg
	lyxscale 20
	scale 20
	rotateAngle 90

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6.8}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Smoothness of a map in terms of charts).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be smooth manifolds, and 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 a continuous map.
 The following are equivalent: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There are atlases 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U\cap F^{-1}(V))\to\mathbb{R}^{m}
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U\cap F^{-1}(V))\to\mathbb{R}^{m}
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

1): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

.
 By (2), 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 By the definition of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map, 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 was an arbitrary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

3): Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 are charts on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 respectively such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap F^{-1}(V)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U\cap F^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop6.7})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

 was an arbitary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U\cap F^{-1}(V))$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U\cap F^{-1}(V))\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

2): Obvious.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Composition of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G:M\to P$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps of manifolds, then the composite 
\begin_inset Formula $G\circ F:N\to P$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(W,\sigma)$
\end_inset

 be charts on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma\circ(G\circ F)\circ\phi^{-1}=(\sigma\circ G\circ\psi^{-1})\circ(\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ G\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are also 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 As a composite of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps of open subsets of Euclidean spaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ(G\circ F)\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $G\circ F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Diffeomorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A 
\series bold
diffeomorpism 
\series default
of manifolds is a bijective 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 whose inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 According to the next two propositions, coordinate maps are diffeomorphisms,
 and conversely, every diffeomorphism of an open subset of a manifold with
 an open subset of a Euclidean space can serve as a coordinate map.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6.10}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, then the coordinate map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\to\phi(U)\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism, so it suffices to check that both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are smooth.
 To test the smoothness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\to\phi(U)$
\end_inset

, we use the atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ (U,\phi)\right\} $
\end_inset

 with a single chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and the atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ (\phi(U),\text{id}_{\phi(U)})\right\} $
\end_inset

 with a single chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{id}_{\phi(U)}\circ\phi\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\phi(U)
\]

\end_inset

is the identity map, it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop6.8})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To test smoothness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to U$
\end_inset

, we use the same atlases as above.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\circ\phi^{-1}\circ\text{id}_{\phi(U)}:\phi(U)\to\phi(U)
\]

\end_inset

is the identity map, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F:U\to F(U)\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism onto an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,F)$
\end_inset

 is a chart in the differentiable structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{\alpha},\phi_{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 in the maximal atlas of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop6.10})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 As composites of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps, both 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi_{\alpha}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}\circ F^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,F)$
\end_inset

 is compatible with the maximal atlas.
 By the maximality of the atlas, the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,F)$
\end_inset

 is in the atlas.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Smoothness in Terms of Components
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In this subsection, we derive a criterion that reduces the smoothness of
 a map to the smoothness of real-valued functions on open sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Smoothness of a vector-valued function) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 be a continuous map.
 The following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 has an atlas such that for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 in the atlas, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Smoothness in terms of components).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a manifold.
 A vector-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if its component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1},\dots,F_{m}:N\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}:N\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Germs of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the set of all pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 Just as in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 case, we introduce an equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 and say that 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\sim(g,V)$
\end_inset

 if there is an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subset U\cap V$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g$
\end_inset

 when restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 The equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
germ 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 for the set of all germs of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 be represent a germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{0},\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{0}\cap U,\phi_{\mid U})$
\end_inset

 is a chart centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\sim(f\mid_{U_{0}\cap U},U_{0}\cap U)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we may always assume that a germ can be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we obtain an isomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\phi}:C_{p}^{\infty}(M)\to C_{p}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),
\]

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\mapsto(f\circ\phi^{-1},\phi(U))$
\end_inset

.
 Of course this map depends on our choice of chart.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 was another chart, then we'd obtain another isomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\varphi}:C_{p}^{\infty}(M)\to C_{p}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),
\]

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\mapsto(f\circ\varphi^{-1},\varphi(U))$
\end_inset

.
 We can relate these two isomorphisms via the transition function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\circ\varphi^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We describe the structure of a premanifold as follows: if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{M}(U):=\{f:U\to\mathbb{R}\mid f|_{U\cap U_{i}}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}:\phi_{i}(U\cap U_{i})\to\mathbb{R}\text{ is }C^{\infty}\}=\{f:U\to\mathbb{R}\mid f\text{ is }C^{\infty}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see that this is a premanifold, fix 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq U_{i_{0}}$
\end_inset

 open let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a map such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi_{i_{0}}^{-1}:\phi_{i_{0}}(U_{i_{0}}\cap U)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{M}(U)$
\end_inset

 because the change of charts between 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-diffeomorphisms.
 Indeed, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f|_{U\cap U_{i}}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}=(f\circ\phi_{i_{0}}^{-1})\circ(\phi_{i_{0}}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i_{0}}$
\end_inset

 yields an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i_{0}},\mathcal{O}_{M|U_{i_{0}}})\cong(Y_{i_{0}},\mathcal{O}_{i_{0}})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is the sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $(M,\mathcal{O}_{M})$
\end_inset

 is a ringed space that is locally isomorphic to a manifold.
 Hence it is a premanifold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of Smooth Maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We show that the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:\mathbb{R}\to S^{1}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $F(t)=(\cos t,\sin t)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}.$
\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, we use the atlas which consists of a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R},\text{id})$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 we use the atlas which consists of the charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{3},\phi_{3})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{4},\phi_{4})$
\end_inset

 where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=\{(a,b)\in S^{1}\mid a>0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{2}=\{(a,b)\in S^{2}\mid a<0\}\qquad\phi_{2}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{3}=\{(a,b)\in S^{2}\mid b>0\}\qquad\phi_{3}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{4}=\{(a,b)\in S^{2}\mid b<0\}\qquad\phi_{4}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us do some computations.
 First, let's compute the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{14}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{14}(a) & =\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{4}^{-1}(a)\\
 & =\phi_{1}\left(a,\sqrt{1-a^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\sqrt{1-a^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similar computations shows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{13}(a) & =\sqrt{1-a^{2}}\\
\phi_{24}(a) & =\sqrt{1-a^{2}}\\
\phi_{23}(a) & =\sqrt{1-a^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now, we need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}\circ F\circ\text{id}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset

.
 Let's compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}\circ F\circ\text{id}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\phi_{1}\circ F\circ\text{id})(t) & =\phi_{1}(F(t))\\
 & =(\phi_{1}((\cos t,\sin t))\\
 & =\sin t.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similar computations shows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\phi_{2}\circ F\circ\text{id})(t) & =\sin t\\
(\phi_{3}\circ F\circ\text{id})(t) & =\cos t\\
(\phi_{4}\circ F\circ\text{id})(t) & =\cos t.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

These maps are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:N\to M$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)=(t^{2},t^{3})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 be the unit sphere with its smooth structure given in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{examplesphere})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:S^{2}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(a,b,c)=c^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, we need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(a,b,c)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 First assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U_{6}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{6},\phi_{6})$
\end_inset

, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(f\circ\phi_{6}^{-1})(a,b) & =f\left(\phi_{6}^{-1}(a,b)\right)\\
 & =f\left(a,b,\sqrt{1-a^{2}-b^{2}}\right)\\
 & =1-a^{2}-b^{2},
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us show that a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 restricts to a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-function on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 To avoid confusing functions with points, we will denote a point on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(a,b)$
\end_inset

 and use 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 to mean the standard coordinate functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $x(a,b)=a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(a,b)=b$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that we can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 restrict to 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $i:S^{1}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $i(p)=(x(p),y(p))$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

, and so the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{S^{1}}=f\circ i$
\end_inset

 with be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 too.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider first the function 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 We use the following atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},\phi_{i})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=\{(a,b)\in S^{1}\mid b>0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{2}=\{(a,b)\in S^{1}\mid b<0\}\qquad\phi_{2}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{3}=\{(a,b)\in S^{1}\mid a>0\}\qquad\phi_{3}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{4}=\{(a,b)\in S^{2}\mid a<0\}\qquad\phi_{4}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a coordinate function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

, it is a coordinate function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cup U_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{3}$
\end_inset

, it suffices to check the smoothness of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\circ\phi_{3}^{-1}:\phi_{3}(U_{3})\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\circ\phi_{3}^{-1})(b)=x\left(\sqrt{1-b^{2}},b\right)=\sqrt{1-b^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{3}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq\pm1$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{1-b^{2}}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 On 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{4}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\circ\phi_{4}^{-1})(b)=x\left(-\sqrt{1-b^{2}},b\right)=-\sqrt{1-b^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

which is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is not equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on the four open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1},U_{2},U_{3},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{4}$
\end_inset

, which cover 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The proof that 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 is similar.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 be the unit sphere with its smooth structure given in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{examplesphere})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Let's construct a smooth function on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 First note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{1}(U_{16})=\{(b,c)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid b^{2}+c^{2}<1\text{ and }c<0\}\qquad\text{and}\qquad\phi_{6}(U_{16})=\{(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid a^{2}+b^{2}<1\text{ and }0<a\}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\phi_{1}(U_{16})\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 be given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(b,c)=b^{2}+c^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Let's pullback 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\phi_{1}(U_{16})\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{16}^{*}(f):\phi_{6}(U_{16})\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 using the transition function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{16}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{16}(a,b) & =\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{6}^{-1}(a,b)\\
 & =\phi_{1}\left(a,b,\sqrt{1-b^{2}-a^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\left(b,\sqrt{1-b^{2}-a^{2}}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We have, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{16}^{*}(f)(a,b) & =(f\circ\phi_{16})(a,b)\\
 & =f\left(b,\sqrt{1-b^{2}-a^{2}}\right)\\
 & =1-a^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Diffeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to the open unit ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x:=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\mapsto\left(\frac{x_{1}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}},\dots,\frac{x_{n}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right):=\beta(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

 with inverse given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x:=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\mapsto\left(\frac{x_{1}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}},\dots,\frac{x_{n}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right):=\beta^{-1}(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let us first check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(x)\in B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|\beta(x)\| & =\sqrt{\left(\frac{x_{1}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}+\cdots+\left(\frac{x_{n}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =\sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\\
 & <\sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\\
 & =1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(x)\in B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Next we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is smooth.
 This comes down to checking the component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 are smooth:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x:=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\mapsto\frac{x_{i}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}:=\beta_{i}(x).
\]

\end_inset

This follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is smooth follows by the same reasoning.
 Finally, checking that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(\beta^{-1}(x))=x$
\end_inset

 is tedious but trivial: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\beta(\beta^{-1}(x)) & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\frac{x_{i}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}}}\left(\frac{x_{1}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}},\cdots,\frac{x_{n}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\left(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\right)\\
 & =\left(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A map smooth map from 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to describe a smooth map from the unit ball 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{1}$
\end_inset

 to the unit sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The idea will be to work in local charts and find a smooth map there.
 Then pull this back to a partial map from 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, we will need to extend it by a continuity argument.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 be the chart in 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{1}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U:=\{x\in D^{1}\mid\|x\|\neq1\text{ and }x\notin[0,1]\times\{0\}\}\qquad\text{and}\qquad\varphi(x):=\varphi(x_{1},x_{2})=(\arctan(x_{2}/x_{1}),\|x\|):=(\theta,r)
\]

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is the unit disk minus its boundary and the line segment from 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 corresonds to polar coordinates.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 be the chart in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V:=\{x\in S^{2}\mid x\notin[0,1]\times\{0\}\times\mathbb{R}^{2}\}\qquad\text{and}\qquad\psi(x):=\psi(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})=(\arctan(x_{2}/x_{1}),\arcsin(x_{3})):=(\theta,\psi)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the unit sphere minus the arc segment from 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1,0)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,-1,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 corresponds to spherical coordaintes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now with respect to these coordinates, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi\colon\varphi(U)\to\varphi(V)$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Phi(\theta,r)=(\theta,\pi(r-1/2)).
\]

\end_inset

Clearly this is a smooth map.
 
\end_layout

